<p>In example 1.10(c), the given compound proposition has a truth value <m>F</m> for every possible combination of assignments of truth values for the component propositions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>. Thus <m>\left( p \Longrightarrow q \right) \Longleftrightarrow (p \land \neg q)</m> is a contradiction.</p>
<p><alert>Remark:</alert></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>In a truth table, if a proposition is a tautology, then every line in its column has <m>T</m> as its entry; if a proposition is a contradiction, every line in its column has <m>F</m> as its entry.</p></li>
<li><p>Two compound propositions <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are equivalent if and only if “<m>P\mathbf{\Longleftrightarrow}Q</m>” is a tautology.</p></li>
</ol>
