<p>Therefore, we have <em>x</em> ≥ <em>a</em> or <em>x</em> ≤ − <em>a</em>. This means that the hyperbola consists of two parts, called its <em>branches</em>. Moreover, if we solve for <em>y</em> from the equation we get <image source="/media/png72/imageC2364.png" /> as <em>x</em> → ∞.</p>
<p>This means the hyperbola will approach (but never reaches) the line <image source="/media/png72/imageC2365.png" /> as <em>x</em> gets larger and larger. That is, the lines <image source="/media/png72/imageC2365.png" /> are the <alert>asymptotes</alert> of the hyperbola.</p>
<p>In sketching a hyperbola, it is best to draw the rectangle formed by the line <em>y</em> = ±<em>b</em> and <em>x</em> = ±<em>a</em> and the to draw the asymptotes which are along the diagonals of the rectangle (as shown by the dashed lines in Figure 4.25). The hyperbola lies outside the rectangle and inside the asymptotes. It opens around the foci.</p>
